<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-446-952  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 446 952.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  May 15 1990 n1425* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Demax seeks to calm scared DEC users with automated networksecurity system. (Demax Software Ltd. Securemax and Securenodesecurity management software) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   DEMAC Software Ltd. (product introduction).andO;Product:   DEC VAX (Minicomputer) (computer programs)Securemax (Data security software) (product introduction)SecureNode (Data security software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSecurity SoftwareNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DEMAX SEEKS TO CALM SCARED DEC USERS WITHandM;AUTOMATED NETWORK SECURITY SYSTEMandM;London SW19-based DEC utilities supplier Demax Software Ltd is claiming afirst in the provision of automated security maintenance over DEC VAXnetworks with two new products based on its Securepak 3.0 VAX securitymanagement software now instal-led in around 3,000 sites.andP;  The new Securemaxsoftware is installed on the network from which the user decides security isbest monitored, then collects and analyses security information sent to it bySecurenode modules resident on remote nodes, either on a corporate network orin the same building.andP;  From installation, the user establishes the desiredlevel of access to each terminal on the network by running the Securemaxprogram, which firstly analyses the existent security features on the networkand makes a series of suggestions on how security can be enhanced or modified- these suggestions are then either rejected or accepted by the useraccording to the network requirements; once this level of security isestablished, any changes made to the network that may affect security arecontinuously monitored by the system.andP;  If problems related to computer crimeor misuse are discovered, Securemax will generate a Digital Control Languagecommand file to correct the problem - this file can then be transferred tothe remote node for implementation.andP;  Since its formation in April 1989, DemaxSoftware has noticed that the traditionally lethargic attitude towardssecurity products is changing: with the release of Securemax and Securenode,Demax intends to capitalise on the widespread increase in computernetworking, which has also brought with it an increase in the opportunitiesfor computer crime and misuse.andP;  For Demax founder and chief executive KevinKalkhoven this has meant that &quot;the traditional slow-sell of securityutilities&quot; is speeding up, with several financial institutions alreadyshowing an interest, and at least one - anonymous - Securemax-Securenodeinstallation so far.andP;  Securemax comes in at #15,000, and Securenode, which isavailable with a local security analysis feature, costs between #225 and #750depending on the type of VAX.andO;</TEXT></DOC>